  "final_answer": "## Space Segment Adjusted EBITDA — Starship R&D Reallocation Analysis\n\n### Reported Figures (FY2025, Recast Consolidated Entity)\n\n| Metric | Amount |\n|---|---|\n| Space Segment Revenue | $4,086M |\n| Starship R&D (allocated to Space segment) | $3,004M |\n| Space Segment Income (Loss) from Operations | $(657)M |\n| **Reported Space Segment Adjusted EBITDA** | **$653M** |\n\n*Reconciliation from GAAP: $(657)M + $757M D&A + $515M SBC + $38M impairment = $653M*\n\n---\n\n### Adjusted Scenario: Starship R&D as Unallocated Corporate Expense\n\nIf the $3,004M of Starship R&D were reclassified from a Space segment expense to an unallocated corporate expense:\n\n| Metric | Reported | Reclassified | Change |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Income from Operations | $(657)M | **$2,347M** | +$3,004M |\n| **Segment Adjusted EBITDA** | **$653M** | **$3,657M** | **+$3,004M** |\n| Adjusted EBITDA Margin | 15.98% | **89.50%** | +73.52 pp |\n\n**Calculation:** $653M + $3,004M = **$3,657M**\n\n---\n\n### What This Indicates About Segment-Level Profitability Presentation\n\n**1. The Space segment's core operations are extraordinarily profitable.** Stripped of Starship development costs, the Space segment would generate $3,657M of Adjusted EBITDA on $4,086M of revenue — an 89.50% margin. This reflects the mature, cash-generative Falcon 9/Falcon Heavy launch business and government contracts (NASA CRS, DoD).\n\n**2. Starship R&D consumes 73.5% of segment revenue.** The $3,004M in Starship R&D is nearly three-quarters of the Space segment's entire top line. This single program is the dominant cost driver, turning what would be a GAAP operating profit of $2,347M into a GAAP operating loss of $(657)M.\n\n**3. The segment boundary obscures true economic performance.** By allocating Starship R&D entirely to the Space segment, the filing presents the segment as barely profitable on an Adjusted EBITDA basis ($653M, 16.0% margin) and loss-making on a GAAP basis. In reality, Starship is a **corporate-level strategic investment** in next-generation infrastructure — analogous to a new product line or platform bet — that benefits the entire consolidated entity (particularly the Connectivity segment, which will be the primary Starship customer for Starlink satellite deployment). The filing itself acknowledges that post-commercialization, Starship costs will be depreciated into the cost of revenue of whichever segment receives the payload — confirming its cross-segment nature.\n\n**4. Segment Adjusted EBITDA is not a clean measure of segment operating performance here.** Because the CODM evaluates segments based on Segment Income from Operations (which includes Starship R&D), the reported profitability metric embeds a massive, discretionary, pre-commercialization investment program. Investors evaluating the Space segment's standalone earning power must adjust for this allocation to avoid significantly understating the segment's true contribution.\n\n**5. The presentation creates a cross-subsidy narrative.** The Space segment is effectively funding Starship development from its Falcon 9 cash flows. This is economically rational (Starship will eventually serve all segments), but the segment-level P&L makes the Space segment appear to be the \"problem child\" with declining profitability (from $1,154M in FY2024 to $653M in FY2025), when in fact the decline is entirely attributable to a 63.7% year-over-year increase in Starship R&D spending ($1,835M → $3,004M).\n\n**Bottom line:** The Space segment's reported Adjusted EBITDA of $653M is an artifact of cost allocation, not a reflection of underlying segment economics. Reclassifying Starship R&D as a corporate investment reveals a segment generating ~$3.7 billion in Adjusted EBITDA at ~90% margins — one of the most profitable launch-service businesses in history — while simultaneously funding a $3 billion bet on the future of the entire enterprise.\n\n---\n\n{\n  \"sources\": [\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm\",\n      \"name\": \"SpaceX S-1 Registration Statement (filed May 20, 2026)\"\n    }\n  ]\n}",
